BSE? sheep - USA (Vermont) 2000.2941
1999 BSE: possible in sheep 990504233612

[1
Date: Mon, 17 Jul 2000 15:24:04 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Associated Press Wire Service, 17 Jul 2000 [edited


The owners of 3 flocks of sheep imported from Belgium to produce milk are
losing their animals because of the possibility they were infected with a
sheep equivalent of mad cow disease. The disease, officially known as
bovine spongiform encephalopathy or BSE, affected some 180 000 head of
British cattle and has been linked to a similar illness in humans, known
as new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease or nvCJD. More than 50 people have
died so far in Britain after apparently eating contaminated beef.

Tests on 4 slaughtered sheep from a Greensboro farm found evidence of
disease in their brains possibly indicating the presence of BSE, U.S.
Department of Agriculture (USDA) officials said Friday as they ordered the
3 flocks of 376 animals destroyed. The results don't mean the animals
definitely have the same disease causing the outbreak in Great Britain, but
they could have.

"Even the remotest possibility it could be that, I think we have to take
all precautions to protect the livestock industry and subsequently the
public health," said Linda Detwiler, senior staff veterinarian for the USDA.

[The owner of 120 of the animals, said the tests were incomplete and his
animals had shown no symptoms of BSE.

"There has never been a sheep in the whole world that has gotten mad cow
disease," said [the owner. Officials said that was true, although
researchers have been able to infect sheep with BSE in laboratories.
[Experimentally only! - Mod.TG In addition, sheep are susceptible to
scrapie, a disease similar to mad cow disease.

The sheep, a breed called East Friesians, have been quarantined since 1998,
two years after the first of them arrived from Belgium. However, the
farmers have been allowed to sell cheese made from the animals' milk. The
sheep came from an area of Belgium where BSE has been found. They are the
only such flocks in the United States.

The disease is spread when animals eat feed made from the brains of
infected animals, and the USDA said there was a possibility the sheep in
Vermont ate contaminated feed before they were imported. [However, this is
not documented, and the BSE found in Belgium was in cattle, not sheep. -
Mod.TG

