[2
Date: 18 Jul 2000
From: Terry S. Singeltary Sr. <flounder@wt.net> through the Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy -list <BSE-L@UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>
Source: <http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/Times/timfgnusa01003.html>,
18 July 2000 [edited


Sheep imported to Vermont from Europe are to be destroyed after tests
showed they could be infected with a variety of BSE.

The US Agriculture Department ruled that the 376 East Friesian milking
sheep posed a "real danger to the national economy" when routine tests on 4
slaughtered animals found their brains to be infected with a type of
spongiform encephalopathy, possibly Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE).
[But scrapie is a Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathy, similar to BSE.
- Mod.TG

Officials said sheep had never been known to have contracted BSE on farms,
but scientists had been able to infect sheep with BSE in the laboratory.

Farmers brandishing "Save Our Sheep" signs protested the government tests
were inconclusive. Larry Faillace, an East Warren farmer who imported 120
of the sheep for cheese production, said: "There has never been a sheep in
the whole world that has gotten 'mad cow' disease."

******
[3
Date: Mon, 17 Jul 2000 22:50:28 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: The Guardian, 17 Jul 2000 [edited


British to consult with U.S. scientists over 'mad sheep'

British government scientists are to hold urgent talks with their
counterparts in the United States over the discovery sheep imported from
Europe are showing signs of a disease possibly linked to bovine spongiform
encephalopathy(BSE) - "mad cow disease" - in cattle.

Three flocks quarantined in Vermont are being destroyed under the orders of
the US Department of Agriculture (USDA), which has begun tests to establish
whether the disease believed to have spread to humans has also transferred
to sheep. [BSE has only experimentally been produced in sheep. There has
never been a documented case and currently there are no valid scientific
test. - Mod.TG

British scientists have long feared this is possible, although the disease
has been introduced to sheep only in laboratory tests. Now government
experts have commissioned a risk assessment to quantify the threat to human
health if BSE were found in Britain's 40 million sheep.

Beginning in January, all British sheep will be tagged as part of European
Union measures to track major diseases. [The US has a traceback system for
cattle that could be applied to these sheep. - Mod.TG

"There is nothing to suggest what they have discovered in America is BSE at
the moment," said a spokesman for the British Ministry of Agriculture. "But
whatever they discover we will look at with interest."
The USDA investigations could take several years. Four of the 376 sheep
were found to have a BSE-like disease, which could be a new form of
scrapie, a sheep disease long endemic in Britain but not known to be
dangerous to humans.

The tests will be conducted at a secure facility at Plum Island, near New
York. The animals were dairy sheep imported from Belgium and the
Netherlands in 1996 and their milk, and cheese made from it, has been sold
for some time. Their lambs have also been sold for food. [The British have
sold calves from animals later testing positive for BSE. When the animals
are below 30 months there does not seem to be concern. So why is there a
concern about these lambs? - Mod.TG

Britain has banned some parts of sheep, including the head, from entering
food for some years but is slightly relaxing controls as a trade-off for
EU-wide measures.

Scrapie is increasing in Britain, with nearly 600 cases reported last year.
The actual incidence may be 8 times as high. It is mostly identified in
older sheep.

